arious factors.","dimension":11,"group":8,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.049116,0.086793,0.09115,0.10197,0.096085,0.094388,0.098481,0.088989,0.083157,0.085138,0.069159,0.055568],"unified_progress":[0.038675,0.073809,0.090313,0.1026,0.10191,0.10219,0.10084,0.094038,0.087872,0.0862,0.068134,0.053417]},{"section":11,"text":"One common cause is a bacterial infection, like Staphylococcus aureus or Streptococcus species, which can lead to bacterial keratitis.","dimension":2,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.033291,0.061876,0.081876,0.093176,0.10201,0.10461,0.10677,0.10308,0.096789,0.088689,0.070466,0.057367],"unified_progress":[0.036629,0.068715,0.087197,0.097394,0.10213,0.10729,0.10399,0.099608,0.092668,0.085022,0.068225,0.051128]},{"section":12,"text":"These infections often present with a corneal ulcer, and the feathery margins might be indicative of the way the infection spreads or the type of bacteria involved.","dimension":2,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.04252,0.051566,0.06779,0.080365,0.095159,0.10351,0.10709,0.10986,0.10595,0.092096,0.077131,0.066965],"unified_progress":[0.0404,0.060186,0.080437,0.092703,0.099008,0.10821,0.10507,0.1019,0.095748,0.088413,0.071888,0.056037]},{"section":13,"text":"Another possibility is a viral infection, such as herpes keratitis, which can also cause ulcers with a feathery appearance.","dimension":2,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.029177,0.052521,0.069212,0.081136,0.09262,0.10022,0.1057,0.10926,0.10768,0.10013,0.083907,0.068436],"unified_progress":[0.034394,0.062681,0.082453,0.094601,0.099014,0.10478,0.10405,0.10153,0.095937,0.089243,0.07357,0.057749]},{"section":14,"text":"However, viral infections are more likely to have a more pronounced or different kind of reaction, and the patient's history of something falling into the eye might lean more towards a bacterial or foreign body cause.","dimension":5,"group":4,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.030254,0.